# Quick Study Guides

**Read before editing:** `docs/lesson-01/quick-study-guide.md`, `docs/lesson-03/quick-study-guide.md`.

## Purpose

Last-minute exam review: dense facts, memory aids, and short-answer practice. Assumes the reader already studied the full guide or plain-language.

## Required structure

```markdown
# Lesson N: Quick Study Guide — Topic

Intro linking plain-language → full guide → quiz.

---

## 1. Big picture
Core design ideas in 3–5 sentences.

---

## 2–N. Numbered topic sections
Tables, bullet facts, !!! tip "Memory aid", !!! warning "Exam point"

---

## High-yield exam questions (or similar)
### 1. Question text?
Short direct answer — 2–6 sentences max.

### 2. ...
...

---

## Quick memory sheet
| Topic | Memory aid |
```

## Content rules

- **Number major sections** (`## 1.`, `## 2.`) for scannable review
- **Tables** for layers, protocols, device comparisons, milestones
- **Exam questions section** — 8–15 questions with **short** answers (not full-lesson depth)
- **Memory aids** — one-liners students can recall under pressure
- **!!! warning "Exam point"** for common wrong answers (OSI 7 vs Internet 5, E2E violations)

## Relationship to other formats

| Full guide | Quick study |
|------------|-------------|
| Full algorithm walkthrough | "Root = smallest ID, block ports that loop" |
| Long prose on history | Milestone table |
| Detailed NAT explanation | "NAT violates E2E — rewrites addresses in the middle" |

Always link siblings in the intro. Update links if quiz/plain-language do not exist yet for that lesson.

## What NOT to do

- Do not duplicate entire full-guide sections — compress
- Do not add `<quiz>` blocks — point to `*-quiz.md`
- Do not use plain-language analogies as the primary explanation — quick study is fact-dense
- Do not skip the memory sheet at the end
